"Q1","A person develops headache and breathlessness on a trekking expedition following rapid ascent to over 3ooo metres above the sea level. which of the following is not used in the treatment of this condition?","a) IV digoxin
b) Descent to lower altitude
c) Administration of oxygen
d) Tablet acetazolamide","The symptoms of headache and breathlessness following rapid ascent indicate acute mountain/altitude sickness and IV digoxin is not used to treat this condition.
on ascent to high altitudes, the low partial pressure of oxygen leads to hypoxia and systemic arteriolar dilatation. Consequently, the capillary pressure rises with increased transudation of fluid into the brain tissue.
Treatment involves administration of oxygen, descent to a lower altitude and administration of acetazolamide. Acetazolamide counteracts hypoxia by stimulating respiration and also reduces the formation of cerebrospinal fluid, thereby reducing intracranial tension.","","A",""
"Q2","V/Q = infinity holds true in which of the following conditions?","a) Foreign body obstruction in the bronchus
b) Equal to dead space
c) when o2 and Co2 ratio is equal
d) The Po2 of alveolar air is 159 mmHg and PCo2 is 4o mmHg","VA /Q= infinity means that there is no exchange of o2 & Co2, which means the volume of the lung equals to dead space and the physiological effort of breathing is wasted.
VA represents the ventilation in alveoli and Q represents the blood flow through the alveolus. The ratio of VA and Q explains the respiratory exchange when there is an imbalance between alveolar ventilation and alveolar blood flow.
VA /Q ratio is infinity when:
• There is adequate ventilation but no perfusion.
• No exchange of gases ( o2 and Co2 )through the respiratory membranes of corresponding alveoli.
• The alveolar air equilibrates the humidified inspired air.","","B",""
