"Q11","what is the site of lesion in wernicke's hemianopic pupil?","a) optic nerve
b) optic tract
c) optic radiation
d) optic chiasma","The site of lesion in wernicke's hemianopic pupil is optic tract.
wernicke hemianopic pupil is the light reflex, where, illumination of the blind half of the retina shows no pupillary reaction while stimulating the normal side of the retina shows a pupillary reaction. It is seen in lesions involving the optic tract. It is also seen in cases such as TB, syphilis and tumours of the optic thalamus.
Homonymous hemianopia (HH) involves loss of vision on the same side of the visual field in both eyes. HH is characteristically seen in lesions involving the visual pathway posterior to the optic chiasma.","","B",""
"Q12","In which of the following reflexes, gastric emptying is delayed when acidic content enters the duodenum?","a) Gastrocolic
b) Enterocolic
c) Gastroileal
d) Enterogastric","In the enterogastric reflex, gastric emptying is delayed when acidic content enters the duodenum.
when the food enters the duodenum, multiple reflexes are initiated from the duodenal wall which passes back to the stomach. These reflexes slow or stop the stomach emptying if the volume of the chyme in the duodenum becomes too much. These reflexes are called enterogastric reflexes.
This reflex can be triggered due to: presence of irritants and acids in duodenal chyme, distension of duodenum, rapid entry of hypertonic or hypotonic fluids, presence of breakdown products of protein digestion and sometimes fat.","","D",""
