"Q17","what makes CpDA superior than ACD for blood storage:","a) The fall in 2, 3 DpG is less
b) Decreased release of o2
c) It has less p5o
d) It is less acidic","The fall in 2, 3 DPG is less when the blood is stored in CPDA compared with ACD.
2, 3 DPG (2,3-diphosphoglycerate) binds to deoxygenated haemoglobin. Therefore, an increase in 2,3 DPG causes increased release of o2 to the tissues.
In stored blood, the 2,3 DPG levels usually fall. As a result, stored blood releases less oxygen to the tissues.
However, such a fall in 2,3 DPG is less when it is stored in a phosphate-containing solution like CPDA (Citrate, phosphate, dextrose, adenine), rather than ACD (Acid citrate dextrose). Therefore, the blood stored in CPDA, in comparison with blood stored in ACD has:
• Higher 2,3 DPG concentration
• Increased release of oxygen to the tissues.
• Raised P5o (Po2 at which Hb is half saturated)","","A",""